 |commanders=''Oblt.z.S.d.R.'' Henri Gosejacob |operations=4 war patrols |victories=no ships sunk }} |}
'''German submarine ''U-713''''' was a [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIC|Type VIIC]] [[U-boat]] of [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' during [[World War II]]. The submarine was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 21 October 1941 at the [[H. C. Stülcken Sohn]] yard at [[Hamburg]], [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 24 September 1942, and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 29 December 1942 under the command of ''[[Oberleutnant zur See]] d.R.'' Henri Gosejacob.
Attached to ''[[8th U-boat Flotilla]]'' based at [[Danzig]], ''U-713'' completed her training period on 30 June 1943 and was assigned to front-line service.
==Design== [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIC|German Type VIIC submarines]] were preceded by the shorter [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIB|Type VIIB submarines]]. ''U-713'' had a displacement of {{convert|769|t|LT}} when at the surface and {{convert|871|t|LT}} while submerged.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} She had a total length of {{convert|67.10|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[pressure hull]] length of {{convert|50.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|6.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a height of {{convert|9.60|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a [[draught (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|4.74|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. The submarine was powered by two [[Germaniawerft]] F46 four-stroke, six-cylinder [[supercharged]] [[diesel engine]]s producing a total of {{convert|2800 to 3200|PS|kW shp|-1}} for use while surfaced, two [[Garbe, Lahmeyer & Co.]] RP 137/c [[Motor–generator|double-acting electric motors]] producing a total of {{convert|750|PS|kW shp}} for use while submerged. She had two shafts and two {{convert|1.23|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} [[propeller]]s. The boat was capable of operating at depths of up to {{convert|230|m}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
The submarine had a maximum surface speed of {{convert|17.7|kn}} and a maximum submerged speed of {{convert|7.6|kn}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} When submerged, the boat could operate for {{convert|80|nmi}} at {{convert|4|kn}}; when surfaced, she could travel {{convert|8500|nmi}} at {{convert|10|kn}}. ''U-713'' was fitted with five {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s (four fitted at the bow and one at the stern), fourteen [[torpedo]]es, one [[8.8 cm SK C/35 naval gun|{{convert|8.8|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} SK C/35 naval gun]], 220 rounds, and an anti-aircraft gun. The boat had a [[Ship's company|complement]] of between forty-four and sixty.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
==Service history== While operating against [[convoy JW 57]] on 24 February 1944, ''U-713'' was spotted by a [[Fairey Swordfish|Swordfish]] from {{HMS|Chaser}}. The destroyer [[HMS Keppel (D84)|HMS ''Keppel'']] was directed towards the U-boat and attacked with depth charges, sinking ''U-713'' in position {{coord|69|27|N|4|53|E|display=title, inline}}.{{sfn|Busch, Röll|1999|p=195}}
